[SkillPath "practice_deals/100_miscellaneous"]
[Student "S"]
{Don't even think of jumping to 2\H. That would show 17+ points. Instead you just bid 1\H, knowing partner is forced to bid again.

Partner does bid again, saying 2\H.  

Partner's rebid promises a minimum opening bid (13-15) and four \Hs. That makes your total about 28 points and ten \Hs. So you bid game. 

East plays 4\H. South leads the \S2, North playing the \SQ.

<b>East plays 4\H. South leads the \S2, North playing the \SQ.</b>

Losers: \S 1 : \H 0 : \D 2 : \C 1 : Total = 4

If the \C finesse works you have no \C loser, and as a bonus you will be able to discard one of your other losers. Even if the finesse fails you still have an extra winner for the discard.

Is there a danger here? Yes. Suppose you win the first trick, pull trumps, then finesse the \C. North might win and play a \S back to South's hand. And South might then lead a \D through dummy's \DK.

South is the Danger Hand. You want to keep him off the lead. His only possible entry is the \S suit, so all you have to do is hold up on the first trick. Win the second \S, pull trumps as before, and finesse the \C. North wins but cannot get to his partner's hand for the killing \D lead. You will discard one of your \D losers on dummy's fourth \C.

You usually think of a hold-up play in a Notrump contract, trying to exhaust one defender of his partner's suit. 

For this deal the hold-up serves a different purpose. It keeps one defender from ever gaining the lead.

You had to lose one \S in any case, so you just choose to lose it to the defender who cannot hurt you.

Notice that the Danger Hand <b>WAS</b> on lead at one point - the opening lead. If South had been clairvoyant enough to lead a \D the contract could have been beaten. Opening leads are important to the defense.}
[Play "W"]S2

